<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,991,1629]" pageId="2" pageNumber="504">
Diagnosis. Body length: about 
<quantity box="[553,621,1100,1124]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.0" pageId="2" pageNumber="504" unit="mm" value="9.0">9 mm</quantity>
, wing length: about 
<quantity box="[853,943,1100,1125]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.5" pageId="2" pageNumber="504" unit="mm" value="8.5">8.5 mm</quantity>
; head black in the ground colour; frons and face with numerous black hairs mixed with many scattered yellowish scaly-hairs; occiput densely covered with white scales; thorax black in the ground colour except the apical part of scuellum which is reddish-brown; Scutum with yellowish scaly-hairs and short black hairs; only basal and side margins of scutellum with white scaly hairs; bristles on Scutum and apical border of scutellum black, mixed with some yellowish hairs on latter; wings with brown basal infuscation, with centers of cells paler; legs with yellowish and black scales, with black bristles; abdomen predominantly black in the ground colour, with the two last segments usually reddish brown; tergites with black, yellowish and white scale bands; tergite 1 white hairy; sides of tergites 2–4 and 6–7 with white scales; tergite 5 with yellowish scales; a band of black scales usually present on the posterior margin of tergite 2; sides of tergites 3–6 with short black hairs. For hypopygium illustration, see 
<bibRefCitation author="Greathead" box="[828,1232,1423,1448]" pageId="2" pageNumber="504" refString="Greathead, D. J. (1980) Insects of Saudi Arabia. Diptera: Family Bombyliidae. Fauna of Saudi Arabia, 2, 291 - 337." type="journal article" year="1980">Greathead (1980: fig. 25, page 327)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,991,1629]" pageId="2" pageNumber="504">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,260,1460,1483]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="504">Note.</emphasis>
The 
<typeStatus box="[317,415,1460,1485]" pageId="2" pageNumber="504">holotype</typeStatus>
of this species is destroyed in 
<collectionCode box="[757,829,1460,1484]" country="Egypt" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/4cts-0w01" name="Entomological Society of Egypt" pageId="2" pageNumber="504">ESEC</collectionCode>
. The designation of a 
<typeStatus box="[1075,1164,1461,1485]" pageId="2" pageNumber="504">neotype</typeStatus>
as name-bearing 
<typeStatus box="[1362,1411,1461,1485]" pageId="2" pageNumber="504">type</typeStatus>
is necessary, however the available specimen in 
<collectionCode box="[671,723,1496,1520]" country="Brazil" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:12997" name="Escola de Florestas" pageId="2" pageNumber="504">EFC</collectionCode>
cannot be designated, it is in a very bad condition, and I could not check some non-type specimens supposed to be preserved in 
<collectionCode box="[894,962,1532,1556]" country="Egypt" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/4cts-0w01" name="Entomological Society of Egypt" pageId="2" pageNumber="504">ESEC</collectionCode>
that was closed 2 years ago for unknown reasons. 
<collectingRegion box="[249,269,1568,1592]" country="Nigeria" name="Rivers" pageId="2" pageNumber="504">A</collectingRegion>
<typeStatus box="[276,365,1568,1592]" pageId="2" pageNumber="504">neotype</typeStatus>
for this species may be warranted in a future study.
</paragraph>
